05135nam a22007095i 9780824853631DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248536317 a10.1515/97808248536312doi  a(DE-B1597)484209  a(OCoLC)930010671  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aSCI0040002bisacsh0483pa523.1qDE-1011 aHasinger, Günther, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAstronomy's Limitless Journey :bA Guide to Understanding the Universe /cGünther Hasinger. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b32 color and 23 black & white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. The Dark Side of the Universe -- tChapter Two. The Big Bang -- tChapter Three. Clearing Up -- tChapter Four. The Cosmic Web of Galaxies -- tChapter Five. Star Formation -- tChapter Six. Wanderers in the Sky -- tChapter Seven. The Stellar Cemetery -- tChapter Eight. Cosmic Monsters -- tChapter Nine. The Destiny of the Universe -- tChapter Ten. And What about God? -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen observing the sky on a very clear, dark night, the soft glow of the Milky Way with its thousands of stars can be seen with the naked eye. Over the centuries since Galileo Galilei first pointed a telescope at the galaxy in 1609, this awe-inspiring yet easily visible panorama was our cosmos, our celestial world. With each new scientific discovery, however, this cosmos has grown dramatically, increasing rapidly over the last several decades. As we look deeper into space, the earlier phases of the cosmos are unveiled to us, but we know that even with the largest telescopes, we will see only a tiny fraction of the vast expanse of the universe. In Astronomy’s Limitless Journey, astrophysicist Günther Hasinger takes the reader on a journey to the far reaches of the universe—an exciting time travel that begins with the incredibly hot fireball of the Big Bang roughly 13.8 billion years ago and ends in distant eons with its cold, dark demise. In between lie the times in which extensive structures, galaxies, stars, and planets form. As the field of astrophysics and cosmology experiences a “golden age” due to larger telescopes, faster computers, and more sophisticated algorithms, fundamental changes are taking place in our understanding of space and time and of the origin and future of our universe. Hasinger thoroughly explains these fascinating revelations and describes the methods utilized in modern astrophysics. He cautions, however, that the boundaries between knowledge and ignorance shift constantly; where our knowledge is so incomplete such that we can only speculate, the journey becomes shaky. Indeed, every new discovery opens a further door to the unknown and with every answered question, we discover more locked doors still to be opened.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCosmology. 7aSCIENCE / Astronomy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070099208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311075236640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780824853631zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824853631423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824853631/original  a978-3-11-056413-6  UHP eBook Package 2014-2016